<H2>U.S. Supreme Court Rules on Physician Assisted Suicide Cases</H2>
In 1996, two <A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/Fed-Ct/">Federal Circuit
Courts
of Appeal</A> struck down laws prohibiting assisted suicide.  The appeals
on these
rulings were heard by the <A HREF="court-links.html">U.S.
Supreme Court</A> January 8, 1997.  The court unanimously overturned both
Circuit Court rulings on June 26, 1997.   The <A
HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/supcourt/1996-97/assist96.htm">
Washington Post summary and related articles</A> are available on-line.

The decisions are available 
from the
<A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/">Legal Information Institute (Cornell
Law School):<P>

<UL><LI><A
HREF="http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/96-110.ZS.html">WASHINGTON
et al. v. GLUCKSBERG et al.</A> 96-110.<BR>
<A
HREF="http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/96-110.cpanel.html">Version
for non-Javascript browsers</A> 96-110.

<LI>
<A
HREF="http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/95-1858.ZS.html">VACCO,
ATTORNEY GENERAL OF NEW YORK, et al. v. QUILL et al.</A> 95-1858.<BR> 
<A
HREF="http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/95-1858.cpanel.html">Version
for non-Javascript browsers</A> 95-1858.
</UL><P>
<A
HREF="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/supcourt/stories/die.htm">Washington
Post On-line articles</A>


<HR>
<H3><A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/Fed-Ct/ca09.html">Ninth
Circuit</A></H3><H4>Oregon</H4>
On November 8, 1994, Oregon voters approved <A
HREF="http://www.islandnet.com/~deathnet/ergo_orlaw.html">
Measure 16</A>, the "Death with Dignity Act".  Judge Michael Hogan issued
a <A HREF="http://www.islandnet.com/~deathnet/ergo_Hogan.html">preliminary
injunction</A> 
against the measure on December 27, 1994, and a 
<A HREF="http://www.islandnet.com/~deathnet/ergo_Hogan2.html">permanent
injunction</A> on August 3, 1995. 
On February 27, 1997,  A three-judge panel of the
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals dismissed the challenge to the law. 
On October 14 the Supreme Court declined to hear the challange to the law
<A HREF="http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/101497.ZOR.html">
(Lee v. Harcleroad, #96-1824)</A>. 

 In Oregon, the legislature asked voters to reconsider
"Measure 16" in
a new vote (ballot measure 51).  This measure has been endorsed by the <A
HREF="http://www.aracnet.com/~oahhs/pub/posmsr51.htm">
Oregon Association of Hospitals and Health Systems</A> and is the focus of
a conference at USC: <A
HREF="http://www.usc.edu/dept/law/bioethics/euthanasia-conf.html">
Physician Assistance in Bringing about Death: Can Regulation Work?</A>
Measure 51 was defeated by voters on November 4, 1997 so the law will not 
be repealed.  
<P>

The <A HREF="http://www.ohd.hr.state.or.us/cdpe/chs/pas/pas.htm">Oregon
Death with Dignity Act</A> requires that the Oregon
Health
Division (OHD) monitor compliance with the law, collect information about
the patients and physicians who participate in legal physician-assisted
suicide, and publish an <A
HREF="http://www.ohd.hr.state.or.us/chs/pas/ar-index.htm">annual
statistical report</A>. 
<P>



<H4>Washington State</H4>
On January 25, 1994, <A
HREF="http://www.compassionindying.org/">Compassion in
Dying</A> initiated a legal challenge of Washington State's prohibition
against assisted
   suicide, <A
HREF="http://leginfo.leg.wa.gov/pub/rcw/title_09a/chapter_036/rcw_9a_36_060">
RCW 9A.36.060</A>.
On May 3, 1994, Federal Judge Barbara J. Rothstein rendered a <A
HREF="http://www.rights.org/deathnet/rothstein.html">decision</A>
declaring the law unconstitutional.
On March 9, 1995, a 3-Judge Panel of the Ninth District <A
HREF="http://www.rights.org/deathnet/ninth_circ.html">Court of Appeals
overturned</A> the District Court (2-1).
On March 6, 1996 the Ninth District Court (en banc) reinstated the
District Court ruling.  
The <A
HREF="http://www.rights.org/deathnet/us9.html">decision</A>
and <A HREF="http://www.rights.org/deathnet/us9B.html">
dissent</A>
are
available via <A
HREF="http://www.islandnet.com/~deathnet/">Deathnet</A>.
<P>
<H3><A HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/2ndCircuit/">Second Circuit</A></H3>
On July 20, 1994, Compassion in Dying filed a 
<A HREF="http://www.islandnet.com/~deathnet/compassion_ny.html">
complaint for declaratory judgment</A> on behalf of 3 New York physicians
and 3 
terminally ill patients. On Dec 15, 1994, US District Court 
Chief Judge Thomas P, Griesa <A
HREF="http://www.islandnet.com/~deathnet/Griesa.html">
upheld New York law</A> prohibiting assisted
suicide (penal law sections <A
HREF="gopher://Leginfo.LBDC.State.NY.US:70/0/.laws/Penal/.PEN120.30">
120.30</A> and <A
HREF="gopher://Leginfo.LBDC.State.NY.US:70/0/.laws/Penal/.PEN125.15">
125.15</A>. On April 2, 1996, a 3-judge panel of the <A
HREF="http://www.law.pace.edu/legal/us-legal/judiciary/second-circuit.html">
2nd Circuit Court of Appeals</A> struck down those laws as relates to
physicians and terminally ill patients (Quill v.
Vacco).
The <A
HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/2ndcircuit/april96/95-7028.html">
decision</A>, and <A 
HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/2ndcircuit/april96/95-7028.html#conc">
concurrence</A> are available from <A 
HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/">
Touro Law Center</A> and <A 
HREF="http://www.law.pace.edu/">Pace University School of Law</A>.<HR>
